          "body": "The four exemptions in vv. 5-8 are among the most humane provisions in ancient warfare legislation. The first three — new house not yet dedicated, new vineyard not yet enjoyed, new betrothed woman not yet married — all share a structural logic: a legitimate good has been initiated but not consummated. The man who built a house he has not yet lived in, who planted vines he has not yet tasted, who betrothed a woman he has not yet married — this man has legitimate competing claims on his presence. Peter Craigie (NICOT, Deuteronomy, 1976) notes that these exemptions reflect Israel's understanding that civilian life has covenantal priority over military service when the two genuinely conflict. The fourth exemption (v. 8) is categorically different: the fearful and fainthearted man is not sent home to protect him but to protect the unit. Fear is contagious — 'he might make his brothers' hearts melt like his heart.' The Hebrew verb masas (melt) pictures the emotional dissolution of a fighting force, unit by unit, starting from a single frightened man. The exemption is therefore a form of military discipline — not punishment, but quarantine. Notably, the man is not shamed or executed; he is simply sent home. The army that remains after the exemption process is the army that has chosen, without illegitimate compulsion, to be there."
