          "title": "Two-tier warfare: the distinction between distant and Canaanite cities",
          "body": "The chapter's most theologically complex section is the distinction between distant cities (vv. 10-15) and Canaanite cities (vv. 16-18). For distant cities, the terms are comparatively merciful by ancient Near Eastern standards: first offer peace, accept surrender and put the people to forced labor, fight only if the city refuses and kill only the men, take women and children and spoil as booty. The standard for Canaanite cities appears to be absolute: nothing that breathes is left alive (v. 16), and the cherem (devoted destruction) applies across all six named peoples (v. 17). The rationale is stated with unusual explicitness in v. 18: 'so that they may not teach you to do according to all their detestable things which they have done for their gods, so that you would sin against the LORD your God.' The threat is spiritual and cultic, not merely military. The Canaanite peoples' religious practices — child sacrifice, sacred prostitution, divination — are documented throughout the Old Testament (Lev. 18:24-28; Deut. 12:31; 18:9-12) as incompatible with Yahweh-worship. The cherem is, on Moses' own terms, a form of covenant quarantine. Calvin notes in his Commentary on Deuteronomy that the severity of the command reflects the severity of what Israel would become if the Canaanite religion was allowed to take root among them — not a minor doctrinal deviation but a wholesale departure from the God who redeemed them. The limited, covenantally bounded nature of the cherem is itself significant: it applies to six named peoples in one geographically defined region at one covenantally specific moment. It does not authorize Israel or any subsequent nation to conduct total warfare at will."
