          "body": "The chapter's final two verses (19-20) are among the most remarkable provisions in the Old Testament's military legislation. In the midst of extended siege warfare — a situation of maximum stress, maximum time pressure, and maximum temptation to strip every available resource — Moses forbids the cutting down of fruit trees. The rhetorical question of v. 19 is the key: 'For is the tree of the field a man, that it should be besieged by you?' The tree has done nothing. It feeds people. It belongs to the land Israel is receiving as inheritance from God. To destroy it in siege rage would be to punish the wrong object — to treat the land as if it were the enemy. The distinction between fruit trees (protected) and non-fruit trees (available for siegeworks) is a concrete application of the principle that war must remain proportional and targeted. Creation is not an appropriate victim of human conflict. This law anticipates what later Christian theology calls the principle of discrimination in just-war theory: combatants and non-combatants must be distinguished, and in this case the distinction extends to trees. The Canaanite peoples are under judgment; the land they inhabit is not. Israel is receiving a good land — a land flowing with milk and honey — and that land's fruitfulness must be stewarded, not squandered, even under the pressure of conquest."
