          "body": "Deuteronomy 20 belongs to a wider canonical pattern of 'holy war' theology in the Old Testament, sometimes called the Divine Warrior motif. Exodus 15:3 declares 'The LORD is a warrior'; Psalm 24:8 calls Him 'mighty in battle'; Isaiah 42:13 pictures Him going out like a warrior. The pattern culminates in Revelation 19:11-16, where the risen Christ appears as the Divine Warrior on a white horse, waging righteous war. The New Testament does not re-authorize Israel's cherem for the church — the book of Hebrews makes clear that the Levitical priesthood, the land promise, and the covenant-people categories have been transformed in Christ (Heb. 8-10). But the theological nerve of Deuteronomy 20 — that God fights for His people, that courage is grounded in His presence rather than in human superiority, and that the people of God are to enter every conflict in confident dependence on Him — remains canonical and directly applicable. The priest's liturgy of vv. 3-4 becomes, in the New Testament, Ephesians 6:10-18: 'Be strong in the Lord and in the strength of His might.' The 'armor of God' passage does with the spiritual warfare of the church what the priest's address does with the military warfare of Israel — it regrounds courage not in the visible strength of the soldier but in the presence and power of the God who fights."
