        "body": "The transition to vv. 10-15 is abrupt but deliberate. From the pre-battle theological preparation of vv. 1-9, Moses moves to the siege protocols for cities outside Canaan. The first instruction is startling in its simplicity: before fighting, offer peace. The Hebrew is *shalom* — not merely a ceasefire proposal but the offer of wholeness, of a relationship that avoids destruction. The obligation to offer *shalom* before siege means that Israel's warfare, even in its most severe expressions, is never the opening move. It is always preceded by an invitation to avoid it.\n\nThe two-scenario structure of vv. 11-14 mirrors ancient Near Eastern suzerainty treaty logic: accept the terms of the greater power and live under it (v. 11), or refuse and face the full consequences of resistance (vv. 12-13). The terms of acceptance — forced labor (*mas*, v. 11) — are not gentle by modern standards, but in the ancient world they represent survival and integration rather than annihilation. The terms of refusal — siege, conquest, and the killing of all men, with women, children, and spoil taken as booty — are consistent with the general practice of warfare in the ancient Near East, and notably more restrained than what was practiced by Assyria or Babylon in the same period.\n\nCritically, the spoil taken from distant cities is affirmed as legitimate and even described as what 'the LORD your God has given you' (v. 14). The material dimension of warfare is not suppressed or spiritualized away. God's provision for His people included the spoil of their enemies — a direct economic benefit to a people who had been slaves in Egypt with nothing and were now taking their place among the nations. Douglas Moo's observation about Pauline ethics applies here as well: the biblical text does not pretend that material realities are irrelevant; it sanctifies and regulates them.\n\nThe limiting formula of v. 15 — 'thus you shall do to all the cities that are very far from you, which are not of the cities of these nations nearby' — functions as a boundary marker. The protocol of vv. 10-14 is explicitly restricted to distant cities. It is not a universal law of warfare but a covenantally specific provision for a particular category of military engagement. The restriction sets up the contrast with vv. 16-18.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shalom* (peace, vv. 10-11) — wholeness, completeness, well-being; in this context a formal offer of surrender terms. *Mas* (forced labor, v. 11) — corvée labor, the same word used of Israel's bondage in Egypt (Exod. 1:11) — a pointed irony: Israel, freed from *mas* in Egypt, now imposes it on those who surrender. *Shalal* (spoil/booty, v. 14) — property taken in warfare, here explicitly sanctioned as the LORD's gift to Israel."
