        "body": "These three verses are among the most theologically demanding in the Pentateuch and must be interpreted with both exegetical precision and canonical honesty. Moses commands the complete destruction of all living things in the six Canaanite peoples' cities — a command that has generated more objection from both ancient and modern readers than perhaps any other text in the Old Testament. Responsible interpretation requires engaging the text directly.\n\nFour observations about the cherem command constrain its meaning. First, it is covenantally specific: it applies to six named peoples (v. 17) in a geographically defined land at a historically defined moment (the initial conquest). It does not authorize ongoing or universal ethnic warfare. Second, it is God-commanded ('as the LORD your God has commanded you,' v. 17) — Israel acts as instrument, not as independent agent. The agency belongs to God; Israel is the means, not the originator, of the judgment. Third, the rationale is stated with unusual explicitness (v. 18): the cherem prevents the Canaanite peoples from teaching Israel their cultic practices, which would cause Israel to sin against the LORD. This is not ethnic hatred; it is covenant protection. Fourth, even the Canaanite-city protocol begins with an offer of terms (v. 10 applies broadly before the distinction is made) — Joshua 9 records the Gibeonites, a Canaanite people, finding protection through surrender and covenant, which suggests the category was not hermetically sealed.\n\nCalvin, commenting on this passage, argues that God's judgment on the Canaanite peoples was long-deferred (Genesis 15:16: 'the iniquity of the Amorites is not yet complete') — the conquest represents not divine arbitrariness but the culmination of centuries of accumulating moral debt. The six peoples' practices — documented in Leviticus 18:24-28 and Deuteronomy 18:9-12 to include child sacrifice, sexual cult practices, and necromancy — represented the extreme end of ancient religious deviation. The land itself is said to have become defiled by these practices (Lev. 18:25).\n\nThe hardest question remains: how does this command relate to the God of the New Testament? The canon's own answer is found in the progressive unfolding of redemption. The cherem was a historically and covenantally bounded act of divine judgment on specific peoples at a specific moment in redemptive history. Its New Testament analogue is not warfare against any ethnic group but the final judgment of Revelation — where the Divine Warrior of Deuteronomy 20:4 reappears as the rider on the white horse of Revelation 19:11, executing God's justice against the enemies of the new covenant. The church does not wield the cherem; it witnesses to the One who will exercise the final judgment that the cherem typologically pointed toward.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Charam* (devote to destruction, cherem, v. 17) — to place under the ban; to consecrate something irrevocably to God by removing it from human use, in warfare by total destruction. The root carries the sense of something being wholly given over to God — which is why Achan's violation of the cherem in Joshua 7 is treated with such severity: he took for himself what belonged to God. *Toevah* (detestable things, v. 18) — appears 117 times in the OT, used throughout Deuteronomy for cultic practices incompatible with Yahweh-worship (12:31; 13:14; 17:4; 18:9-12; 27:15)."
